Welfare States, Labor Markets, Political Dynamics, and Population Health: A 
Time-Series Cross-Sectional Analysis Among East and Southeast Asian Nations.

Ng E(1), Muntaner C(2), Chung H(3).

Author information:
(1)School of Social Work, Renison University College, University of Waterloo, 
Waterloo, Ontario, Canada.
(2)Bloomberg School of Nursing and Dalla Lana School of Public Health, 
University of Toronto, Toronto, Ontario, Canada School of Health Policy & 
Management, College of Health Science, and Department of Public Health Sciences, 
Graduate School, Korea University, Seoul, Republic of Korea 
carles.muntaner@utoronto.ca.
(3)School of Health Policy & Management, College of Health Science, and 
Department of Public Health Sciences, Graduate School, Korea University, Seoul, 
Republic of Korea.

Recent scholarship offers different theories on how macrosocial determinants 
affect the population health of East and Southeast Asian nations. Dominant 
theories emphasize the effects of welfare regimes, welfare generosity, and labor 
market institutions. In this article, we conduct exploratory time-series 
cross-sectional analyses to generate new evidence on these theories while 
advancing a political explanation. Using unbalanced data of 7 East Asian 
countries and 11 Southeast Asian nations from 1960 to 2012, primary findings are 
3-fold. First, welfare generosity measured as education and health spending has 
a positive impact on life expectancy, net of GDP. Second, life expectancy varies 
significantly by labor markets; however, these differences are explained by 
differences in welfare generosity. Third, as East and Southeast Asian countries 
become more democratic, welfare generosity increases, and population health 
improves. This study provides new evidence on the value of considering politics, 
welfare states, and labor markets within the same conceptual framework.

