Obesity and related consequences to ageing.

Jura M(1), Kozak LP(2).

Author information:
(1)Institute of Animal Reproduction and Food Research, Polish Academy of 
Science, ul. Tuwima 10, 10-748, Olsztyn, Poland. m.jura@pan.olsztyn.pl.
(2)Institute of Animal Reproduction and Food Research, Polish Academy of 
Science, ul. Tuwima 10, 10-748, Olsztyn, Poland. l.kozak@pan.olsztyn.pl.

Obesity has become a major public health problem. Given the current increase in 
life expectancy, the prevalence of obesity also raises steadily among older age 
groups. The increase in life expectancy is often accompanied with additional 
years of susceptibility to chronic ill health associated with obesity in the 
elderly. Both obesity and ageing are conditions leading to serious health 
problems and increased risk for disease and death. Ageing is associated with an 
increase in abdominal obesity, a major contributor to insulin resistance and the 
metabolic syndrome. Obesity in the elderly is thus a serious concern and 
comprehension of the key mechanisms of ageing and age-related diseases has 
become a necessary matter. Here, we aimed to identify similarities underlying 
mechanisms related to both obesity and ageing. We bring together evidence that 
age-related changes in body fat distribution and metabolism might be key factors 
of a vicious cycle that can accelerate the ageing process and onset of 
age-related diseases.

